postcontent:
A clone of the original SPR Mk12 Mod 0 in 6.8spc

The United States Navy Mark 12 Mod 0/1 Special Purpose Rifle (SPR) is a rifle in service with United States Special Operations Forces in Operation Enduring Freedom and previously in Operation Iraqi Freedom. SPR initially stood for Special Purpose Receiver, but that nomenclature has been replaced as the weapon became a stand-alone weapons system, and not just an add-on upper receiver assembly (part of the proposed SOPMOD upgrades). The SPR was eventually type classified by the U.S. Navy as the Mk 12. Note that the weapon was developed by a Navy office (Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane Division) for SOCOM units, not for use by units that fall under the conventional US Navy.

For more detailed information go to Wikipedia and enter> Mk 12 Special Purpose Rifle.

I can ship, also I will detach the upper from the lower and sell separate. This was a very exhausting clone to build. title: For Sale/Trade:  1999 Chevy Silverado 1500 Extended Cab 4x4 - $5,400
location: Beloit, south of Janesville, Janesville, Wisconsin
postcontent:
This truck has been reduced $1,500 in price because it needs new hard brake lines installed, and is a good buy for someone who can install the new lines themselves.  It is a 1999 Chevy Silverado 1500 Extended Cab 4x4 with 124K miles.  The truck is pewter in color.  The full-size gold Guidon bed topper has a full-height hatchback with smoked glass center access locking door and an adjustable top rail system for cargo.  The 6.5-foot truck bed interior itself is in great condition, with no rust.  The tailgate is in the garage and goes with the truck, and it is in perfect condition.

The cab interior is also in great condition, with factory fabric upholstery upgrade.  The dash and console are all in excellent condition, no additional electronics were ever mounted anywhere on it.  The carpet is in very decent shape, and the headliner is still 99%.  There is a problem with the adjustment mechanism under the driver's seat, but I haven't looked into it yet.  The radio works, the windows work, and none of the glass is bad.  The air will freeze you out in summer, and the heater will cook you once the engine warms.

At 93,000 miles, the gas pump malfunctioned and was replaced.

At 112,000 miles, the chassis was fully re-lubed, the 4x4 mechs were inspected and tested, the transfer case lubricant was replaced, the gas filter was replaced, the transmission filter was replaced along with all fresh transmission fluid, and the cooling system was drained, flushed and refilled.

At 119,000 miles, all four brakes were rejuvenated and lifetime pads installed. 
At 121,000 miles the tires were replaced with good all-season 70K radial A/T truck tires.

I bought the truck used with 23K miles on it, and it was regularly serviced at Gordy Boucher Ford of Janesville where I purchased it, and later at Bud Weiser Chevrolet of Beloit after the sale-included service contract expired at Boucher.  The truck had the factory recall work done by Bud Weiser Chevrolet.  The truck has had its oil and filters (both oil and air) and PCV/sensor changes at regular factory intervals or as deemed necessary by the onboard computer system.

The engine is a Vortec 5.3L 16-valve gasoline fuel-injected V-8, 270 HP, with a 4-speed automatic transmission with overdrive and Tow/Haul Shift Modification feature for heavy loads, and it has the Z71 highway suspension.  Other features include:  a heavy-duty 600 amp battery and heavy-duty alternator, stainless steel exhaust, electronic transmission control, automatic locking hubs with push-button 4-wheel-drive and electronic transfer case, skid plates, full-size spare tire, front and rear anti-roll bars, 16”  standard factory alloy wheel rims, speed-sensing power steering, and power ABS disc brakes.  There are no fluid leaks under the truck.

This truck has been used to haul both payload and heavy trailer for both work and recreation.  She’s not as pretty as she was new, and the rocker panels are getting bad due to GM's poor design of breather slots underneath, but the rest of the body panels are in good shape, and the bed is scratched but rock solid.  As stated previously, she has been regularly and well maintained by professionals, and is the most reliable vehicle I have ever owned.  With a few exceptions for short-distance hauling, and taking the family to Florida impromptu without a glitch in 2010, the truck has been parked for the last five and a half years.

I’ll accept cash or bank cashier’s check; I will not accept personal checks.

Remington Nylon 66, .22 LR rifle.  Serial number dates this gun as manufactured in mid-1977.  Classic Black on Black stock/barrel colors.  Small amount of surface rust but will easily wipe off.  Gun is mechanically perfect and fires straight and true with no fouling or misfires.  Rifle was purchased new by my grandfather to teach me and my brothers to shoot.  Always cleaned and stored inside.  this gun was re-discovered wrapped up in an old rug in a corner of the old hall closet as we were cleaning out the old house to sell it.  i havent touched the dust/misc grime that has settled on the outside so i can show the gun exactly as it was found. it will easily wipe clean, but i want to show it honestly and i think the story of this rifle's history is worth telling.....so the buyer can clean it as he wishes!

Remington's Nylon 66 was their 1st attempt at a synthetic stock, mass-produced gun, and they hit a homerun with this one!  These guns are now very collectable and their value seem to keep going up every year.  The Nylon 66 was the gun every boy wanted when they were growning up as a first gun to learn how to shoot, and they are so well-built and reliable that many of them are still around today, shooting just as good as they did 30 years ago!

A clone of the original SPR Mk12 Mod 0 in 6.8spc

The United States Navy Mark 12 Mod 0/1 Special Purpose Rifle (SPR) is a rifle in service with United States Special Operations Forces in Operation Enduring Freedom and previously in Operation Iraqi Freedom. SPR initially stood for Special Purpose Receiver, but that nomenclature has been replaced as the weapon became a stand-alone weapons system, and not just an add-on upper receiver assembly (part of the proposed SOPMOD upgrades). The SPR was eventually type classified by the U.S. Navy as the Mk 12. Note that the weapon was developed by a Navy office (Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane Division) for SOCOM units, not for use by units that fall under the conventional US Navy.

For more detailed information go to Wikipedia and enter> Mk 12 Special Purpose Rifle.

I can ship, also I will detach the upper from the lower and sell separate. This was a very exhausting clone to build. The price reflects my time and energy finding these parts and putting this excellant rifle together. The upper was put together by PRI, and the lower by a Knights Armament armorer.

The Ruger SR1911 is a classically styled pistol designed with all of the modern manufacturing advances that you have come to expect from Ruger.  Original 1911 Series 70 design provides for easy takedown and re-assembly. Slim traditional design
with hardwood grips and checkered backstrap.  Precision CNC-controlled machining process  results in a superior slide-to-frame fit and smooth slide travel. The stainless steel barrel and bushing are produced from the same bar stock, on the same machine, for improved accuracy.  Positive barrel lock-up allows for a superior accuracy out-of-the-box. Oversized ejection port and extended magazine release enhance competition performance.  Lightweight, aluminum, skeletonized trigger features an adjustable over-travel stop and provides a very crisp, no creep, light trigger pull with a quick, positive reset. Skeletonized hammer is lightweight and provides faster cycling.  Dovetailed, 3-dot sight system features a Novak® LoMount Carry rear and standard front sight that combines optimal target acquisition in an ideal carry configuration.  Stainless steel frame and slide feature blasted, low-glare finish and slide serrations for positive grip.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 640-3 Stainless .357 Magnum Revolver
postcontent:
I am selling my  as new in the box Smith & Wesson 640-3 Stainless .357 Magnum Revolver.  Test fired only, then cleaned and put back in the box, and that was only with 38 Special target rounds, not .357.  This is the J Frame model with 2 1/8 inch barrel, which makes an excellent light-weight concealed carry weapon with plenty of knock-down power.  

Price is $600, much less than you would have to pay a gun shop, if you could find one in stock.  I am open to hearing proposals of interesting trades.  Selling only because this is my only .357 and I'm trying to keep guns in few calibers in these days of ammunition shortages.  Honestly, .357 is hard to find, but 38 Special is cheap and plentiful and this gun will fire those rounds as well.

Also included is a combat grip, as well as the boot grip pictured in the photographs.  If you are local I'll throw in a new box of .357 and whatever I have left in 38 Special.

Face to face local transaction (some driving OK if we meet in between).  I will ship anywhere this weapon is legal, but only if you pay actual shipping costs and the FFL fees at both ends.

If you have any question about me, check my eBay feedback.  Have been buying and selling for 15 years with 100% positive feedback, including very high ticket items.  My eBay ID is saludatrader.
